2. Implement the `iterator()` method to return an instance of an inner class that implements `Iterator<T>`.
3. In the inner class, maintain an index to track the current position.
4. Implement `hasNext()` to check if there are more elements.
5. Implement `next()` to return the current element and increment the index, guarding against `NoSuchElementException`.

Here's an example:

```java
import java.util.Iterator;
import java.util.NoSuchElementException;

public class CustomIterable<T> implements Iterable<T> {
    private T[] items;

    public CustomIterable(T[] items) {
        this.items = items;
    }

    @Override
    public Iterator<T> iterator() {
        return new CustomIterator();
    }

    private class CustomIterator implements Iterator<T> {
        private int index = 0;

        @Override
        public boolean hasNext() {
            return index < items.length;
        }

        @Override
        public T next() {
            if (!hasNext()) {
                throw new NoSuchElementException();
            }
            return items[index++];
        }
    }
}
```

This implementation ensures proper iteration over the elements while handling exceptions appropriately.

The issue arises because the `compareTo()` method is incorrectly implemented. In a `TreeMap`, keys that return `0` from `compareTo()` are treated as duplicates and only one entry is retained.

