void increment() {
    counter++; // Not atomic
}
```

The ABA problem occurs in concurrent programming when a value is changed from A to B and then back to A. A compare-and-swap (CAS) operation may mistakenly assume the value hasn't changed, leading to incorrect behavior.

`AtomicStampedReference` addresses this by associating a version stamp with the reference. When performing a `compareAndSet`, it checks both the current value and the associated stamp. If the value is A and the stamp is 1, it will only succeed if the current value is still A and the stamp is still 1, preventing the ABA issue.

Example usage:

```java
AtomicStampedReference<Integer> atomicRef = new AtomicStampedReference<>(1, 1);
int[] stamp = new int[1];
Integer currentValue = atomicRef.get(stamp);
boolean success = atomicRef.compareAndSet(currentValue, 2, stamp[0], stamp[0] + 1);
```

