Instruction reordering is an optimization technique used by compilers and CPUs to improve performance by rearranging the execution order of instructions. This can lead to unexpected behavior in multithreaded environments, as one thread may see stale data if another thread modifies it.

The `volatile` keyword in Java prevents instruction reordering by inserting memory barriers. These barriers ensure that all reads/writes to a volatile variable occur in the order specified in the code. Specifically, no instruction can be reordered before a volatile read/write, and no instruction can be reordered after it. This guarantees visibility and consistency across threads.

Example:

