Double-checked locking (DCL) failed before Java 5 due to instruction reordering. The sequence of operations could occur as follows: 

1. Memory allocation for the singleton instance.
2. Reference assignment to the instance variable.
3. Initialization of the instance.

If another thread reads the reference after step 2 but before initialization, it may see a partially constructed object.

The fix involves using the `volatile` keyword on the singleton instance variable. This ensures that the instance is fully constructed before being visible to other threads:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static volatile Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            synchronized (Singleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {
                    instance = new Singleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
``` 

This guarantees visibility and prevents the creation of partially constructed objects.

The safe publication idiom ensures that an object is fully constructed before being shared between threads, preventing visibility issues. Key methods include:

1. **Static Initializer**: Objects created in a static block are safely published when the class is loaded.
