To design an AST node hierarchy using sealed classes in Java, we can define a sealed interface `Expr` that permits specific implementations for different expression types: `Num`, `Add`, and `Mul`. Here's a concise implementation:

```java
sealed interface Expr permits Num, Add, Mul {
    int eval();
}

final class Num implements Expr {
    final int value;

    Num(int value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    @Override
    public int eval() {
        return value;
    }
}

final class Add implements Expr {
    final Expr left, right;

    Add(Expr left, Expr right) {
        this.left = left;
        this.right = right;
    }

    @Override
    public int eval() {
        return left.eval() + right.eval();
    }
}

final class Mul implements Expr {
    final Expr left, right;

    Mul(Expr left, Expr right) {
        this.left = left;
        this.right = right;
    }

    @Override
    public int eval() {
        return left.eval() * right.eval();
    }
}
```

In this design:
- `Expr` is a sealed interface.
- `Num`, `Add`, and `Mul` are final classes implementing `Expr`.
- Each class implements an `eval()` method to compute its value. 

Pattern matching can be done using a switch statement as hinted.

