    // Task code here
});
```

Structured Concurrency in Java 21 introduces a framework for managing concurrent tasks more effectively. It utilizes `StructuredTaskScope` to group related tasks, ensuring they complete together. If one task fails or succeeds, all tasks in the scope are canceled, treating them as a single unit. This approach simplifies lifecycle management and helps prevent thread leaks by ensuring that resources are properly released when tasks are no longer needed. It enhances readability and maintainability of concurrent code by providing a clear structure. 

Example usage:

```java
try (var scope = new StructuredTaskScope.ShutdownOnFailure()) {
    var task1 = scope.fork(() -> { /* task logic */ });
    var task2 = scope.fork(() -> { /* task logic */ });
    scope.join(); // Wait for all tasks to complete
    // Handle results
}
```

