In Spring Boot, handle the 429 response by implementing a retry mechanism. Use Spring Retry with the `@Retryable` annotation to retry requests that throw `TooManyRequestsException`. 

Example:

```java
import org.springframework.retry.annotation.Backoff;
import org.springframework.retry.annotation.Recover;
import org.springframework.retry.annotation.Retryable;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class ApiService {

    @Retryable(value = TooManyRequestsException.class, maxAttempts = 5, backoff = @Backoff(delay = 2000))
    public ResponseEntity<String> callApi() {
        // API call logic
    }

    @Recover
    public ResponseEntity<String> recover(TooManyRequestsException e) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS).body("Retry limit exceeded");
    }
}
```

Additionally, consider using Resilience4j's `RateLimiter` to control the rate of requests made by your application. This can help prevent hitting the API Gateway's limits.

To configure retry behavior for `@SqsListener` in Spring Cloud AWS 3.x, define an `SqsMessageListenerContainerFactory` bean. Use `SqsContainerOptions` to set parameters like `maxConcurrentMessages`, `maxMessagesPerPoll`, and `pollTimeout`. 

For error handling, implement an `SqsListenerErrorHandler` to manage retries. Alternatively, leverage SQS's built-in visibility timeout for retries and configure a Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) after exceeding `maxReceiveCount`. 

For manual retries, annotate the listener method with `@Retryable`.

Example configuration:

```java
@Bean
public SqsMessageListenerContainerFactory<MyMessage> sqsListenerContainerFactory(AmazonSQSAsync amazonSQS) {
    SqsMessageListenerContainerFactory<MyMessage> factory = new DefaultSqsMessageListenerContainerFactory();
    factory.setAmazonSqs(amazonSQS);
    factory.setContainerOptions(SqsContainerOptions.builder()
